Introduction

This page provides an index into all of the MIT/IL engineering drawings to which we have so far acquired access, the various AGC and DSKY models.  In other words, these are electrical and mechanical drawings.  Our electro-mechanical page organizes some of the electrical drawings from this collection on a unit-by-unit basis, cross-referenced with other useful information, so that you can tell (for example) which electrical schematics are associated with Block II AGC p/n 2003993 or Block I DSKY p/n 1003706.  On this page, on the other hand, we simply try to give you titles and links for each drawing we have, in some cases supplemented by links to our own CAD transcriptions of the original drawings.

Collection of these drawings has become an ongoing process, so the collection is expanding, with no end in sight, so if you don't see a drawing you want, check back again later.  Even better, we might be able to tell you how to acquire a copy for yourself, in which case you can donate it to our collection!

The collection is organized primarily in terms of the "batches" in which we acquired them.  I.e., by where and when we acquired them. You may find that a given drawing appears in several different batches, in which case you can simply choose the one that looks best for your purposes.  A unified index by drawing number would likely be a more-elegant solution, but it's also a lot more work to provide; perhaps someday.  My suggestion is to simply use your browser's text-search feature to find what you need within this page.

Drawings Supplied by Eldon Hall

Once upon a time, AGC developer Eldon Hall provided a subset of the Block II AGC electrical-schematic drawings to the now-essentially-defunct KLABS website.  We now host these drawings locally at the Virtual AGC Project's website, and this is an index into those documents.

A

Stocklist
145

1

B

The original Apollo Program drawing provided a lot of connectivity data in the form of a large table, rather than in the form of wiring.  Therefore, it's not really possible to make a CAD transcription of the drawing which is (at the same time) a good visual representation of the original and an electrically-valid representation of the design.  Two separate CAD transcriptions were created, one of them intended to be visually accurate (containing the original tabular connectivity information) and the other one electrically accurate (replacing the table with wiring).

See also: transcription of drawing to CAD or images rendered from CAD

NARA SW Batch #0

These are drawings that I paid to have scanned at NARA Southwest, in Fort Worth.  The batch consists entirely of an almost-complete set of Block I AGC/DSKY electrical schematics.  It is in the form of a series of PDFs, each of which contain 20 or so drawings.  Perhaps eventually I'll split these up into individually-accessible drawings, but for now I'll just content myself by giving you an index that tells how to find each of the drawings within these PDFs.

NARA SW Batch #1

This is a batch of drawings that I personally scanned over a period of a couple of days at NARA Southwest.  (Well ... I paid for the privilege of scanning them, but that's much cheaper than paying NARA to scan them.)  Among other things, this batch fills in many, but not all, of the gaps in the coverage of Block I schematics, as well as providing numerous significant Block II mechanical drawings.  In reading the table, note that Block I drawings are 100-series drawings, while Block II drawings are 200-series.  The batch has been archived on our Internet Archive site, and the links below are to those archival drawings.

Note that a drawing will typically consist of "sheets" (perhaps sheets 1, 2, and 3), but that sheets were sometimes too wide to be microfilmed in a single frame, and therefore may have several frames each.  The drawing sheets in this batch may have anywhere from 1 to 4 frames.

Note too that in most cases, only the final rev of any given drawing was scanned, but that the earlier revisions are usually also available at NARA.

Finally, note that I wasn't quite up on all the tricks when I made these scans, so some of my scans are quite awful.  I think those have mostly been eliminated from the table below (at least, where it was my fault), but some mediocre scans have probably been retained but are rescanned in later batches.

Specification Control Drawings (SCDs)

SCDs for electrical components are MIT/IL drawings that act something like a manufacturer's datasheet does.  Mike Stewart et al. paid to have a number of these scanned by NARA Southwest, although there there are also many SCDs spread out in the various other sources on this page from which we've obtained drawings.
